<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-01-15T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-01-15T12:00:00-05:00" n="622" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d622">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/6177: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Eberhardt</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-01-15T12:00:00-05:00">January 15,
                                1929—noon</date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>8. Your 17, January 9, 2 p.m. It is the feeling of the Department that
                            this is a matter in which the decision and responsibility should rest
                            with the Government of Nicaragua alone. If martial law is established,
                            it should be carried out by the authorities of Nicaragua only.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>